  ('CISA-00901', 3, 'Medium', 'Vendor and Contract Management', 'What should be the PRIMARY recommendation from the auditor to mitigate the risk associated with the outsourced billing operations?', 'Implement multi-factor authentication for all users accessing the billing system, regardless of location.', 'Require the vendor to provide evidence of a recent independent security audit, such as a SOC 2 report, and review the results.', 'Develop a comprehensive data loss prevention (DLP) policy for sensitive patient billing information.', 'Negotiate a revised contract with stricter penalties for data breaches and compliance violations.', 'B', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (B): Require the vendor to provide evidence of a recent independent security audit, such as a SOC 2 report, and review the results.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''re Wrong:  Option A: Implement multi-factor authentication for all users accessing the billing system, regardless of location. → This approach either ignores the issue, escalates prematurely without documentation, or follows an unstructured process that creates audit gaps. Auditors must always follow structured procedures.  Option C: Develop a comprehensive data loss prevention (DLP) policy for sensitive patient billing information. → This option misses the audit objective or applies the wrong standard. Audit procedures must be aligned with scope and audit standards (ISACA, COBIT).  Option D: Negotiate a revised contract with stricter penalties for data breaches and compliance violations. → This might be a procedural step but not the complete or correct response. Context matters in audit decisions.', 'Obtaining and reviewing a recent independent security audit report provides assurance that the vendor''s security controls are adequately designed and operating effectively. This offers objective evidence of the vendor''s security posture.', 'See reasoning above for explanation of correct vs incorrect choices', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (B): Require the vendor to provide evidence of a recent independent security audit, such as a SOC 2 report, and review the results.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''re Wrong:  Option A: Implement multi-factor authentication for all users accessing the billing system, regardless of location. → This approach either ignores the issue, escalates prematurely without documentation, or follows an unstructured process that creates audit gaps. Auditors must always follow structured procedures.  Option C: Develop a comprehensive data loss prevention (DLP) policy for sensitive patient billing information. → This option misses the audit objective or applies the wrong standard. Audit procedures must be aligned with scope and audit standards (ISACA, COBIT).  Option D: Negotiate a revised contract with stricter penalties for data breaches and compliance violations. → This might be a procedural step but not the complete or correct response. Context matters in audit decisions.'),
