reates audit gaps. Auditors must always follow structured procedures.  Option C: Conduct a vulnerability assessment of the SIS to identify potential security weaknesses. → This option misses the audit objective or applies the wrong standard. Audit procedures must be aligned with scope and audit standards (ISACA, COBIT).  Option D: Increase the MTD for the SIS in the BIA to match the existing RTO. → This might be a procedural step but not the complete or correct response. Context matters in audit decisions.', 'The RTO exceeding the MTD indicates a significant risk of business disruption and financial loss. The auditor should first recommend revising the BCP and DRP to ensure recovery capabilities align with the business requirements defined in the BIA. This proactive approach mitigates potential damage to the university''s operations.', 'See reasoning above for explanation of correct vs incorrect choices', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (B): Revise the BCP and disaster recovery plan (DRP) to align the RTO with the MTD identified in the BIA.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''re Wrong:  Option A: Implement a hot site for the SIS to reduce the RTO. → This approach either ignores the issue, escalates prematurely without documentation, or follows an unstructured process that creates audit gaps. Auditors must always follow structured procedures.  Option C: Conduct a vulnerability assessment of the SIS to identify potential security weaknesses. → This option misses the audit objective or applies the wrong standard. Audit procedures must be aligned with scope and audit standards (ISACA, COBIT).  Option D: Increase the MTD for the SIS in the BIA to match the existing RTO. → This might be a procedural step but not the complete or correct response. Context matters in audit decisions.'),
  ('CISA-00936', 4, 'Medium', 'Business Continuity and Disaster Recovery', 'What should the auditor FIRST recommend?', 'Implement a disk-to-disk backup solution to improve backup speed.', 'Review and enforce the tape rotation schedule and perform regular test restores of the research data.', 'Increase the frequency of backups from daily to hourly.', 'Procure a new tape drive to improve backup reliability.', 'B', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (B): Review and enforce the tape rotation schedule and perform regular test restores of the research data.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''re Wrong:  Option A: Implement a disk-to-disk backup solution to improve backup speed. → This approach either ignores the issue, escalates prematurely without documentation, or follows an unstructured process that creates audit gaps. Auditors must always f