king techniques on all production data within the test environment. → This approach either ignores the issue, escalates prematurely without documentation, or follows an unstructured process that creates audit gaps. Auditors must always follow structured procedures.  Option C: Implement a more robust change management process to ensure security configurations are synchronized between all environments. → This option misses the audit objective or applies the wrong standard. Audit procedures must be aligned with scope and audit standards (ISACA, COBIT).  Option D: Conduct regular vulnerability scans of the test environment to identify and remediate potential security weaknesses. → This might be a procedural step but not the complete or correct response. Context matters in audit decisions.', 'Using a test environment containing production data as a disaster recovery warm site creates a significant risk of data breaches and compliance violations. Recommending a separate, isolated environment as the warm site is paramount to protect sensitive data and maintain regulatory compliance during a disaster recovery scenario.', 'See reasoning above for explanation of correct vs incorrect choices', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (B): Update the disaster recovery plan (DRP) to designate a separate, isolated environment as the warm site.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - 