  ('CISA-00942', 4, 'Hard', 'Business Continuity and Disaster Recovery', 'What action should the auditor take to address this finding?', 'Recommend a security assessment of the PLCs to identify vulnerabilities in the OT environment.', 'Inform the audit committee of the material weakness in the BCP regarding the omission of the OT environment and its potential financial impact due to insurance policy exclusions.', 'Review the incident response plan (IRP) to determine if it includes specific procedures for responding to cyber incidents affecting the OT environment.', 'Advise the organization to implement network segmentation to isolate the OT environment from the IT network.', 'B', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (B): Inform the audit committee of the material weakness in the BCP regarding the omission of the OT environment and its potential financial impact due to insurance policy exclusions.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''re Wrong:  Option A: Recommend a security assessment of the PLCs to identify vulnerabilities in the OT environment. → This approach either ignores the issue, escalates prematurely without documentation, or follows an unstructured process that creates audit gaps. Auditors must always follow structured procedures.  Option C: Review the incident response plan (IRP) to determine if it includes specific procedures for responding to cyber incidents affecting the OT environment. → This option misses the audit objective or applies the wrong standard. Audit procedures must be aligned with scope and audit standards (ISACA, COBIT).  Option D: Advise the organization to implement network segmentation to isolate the OT environment from the IT network. → This might be a procedural step but not the complete or correct response. Context matters in audit decisions.', 'The omission of the OT environment from the BCP and its implications for the company''s insurance coverage represent a material weakness with potentially significant financial consequences. Informing the audit committee is crucial for escalating the issue to the appropriate level of governance and ensuring timely corrective action, because there is a direct correlation to the financial impact.', 'See reasoning above for explanation of correct vs incorrect choices', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (B): Inform the audit committee of the material weakness in the BCP regarding the omission of the OT environment and its potential financial impact due to insurance policy exclusions.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: 