findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''re Wrong:  Option A: The CIO may lack the business knowledge necessary to accurately assess the impact of system disruptions on critical business functions. → This approach either ignores the issue, escalates prematurely without documentation, or follows an unstructured process that creates audit gaps. Auditors must always follow structured procedures.  Option C: Assigning the declaration solely to the CIO creates a single point of failure, potentially hindering timely response in case of their unavailability. → This option misses the audit objective or applies the wrong standard. Audit procedures must be aligned with scope and audit standards (ISACA, COBIT).  Option D: The absence of clearly defined roles and responsibilities for communication during a disaster event could lead to confusion and delays in stakeholder notification. → This might be a procedural step but not the complete or correct response. Context matters in audit decisions.'),
  ('CISA-00945', 4, 'Hard', 'Business Continuity and Disaster Recovery', 'What should the auditor FIRST recommend to mitigate the risks associated with future transaction backlogs?', 'Implement automated scripts to expedite the processing of historical transactions using increased computational resources after system recovery.', 'Develop a documented procedure outlining prioritization criteria and resource allocation for processing accumulated transactions within regulatory timeframes after an incident.', 'Increase the frequency of system backups to minimize data loss and reduce the volume of transactions needing reprocessing after an outage.', 'Enhance cybersecurity defenses by deploying additional intrusion detection and prevention systems to reduce the likelihood of future cyberattacks.', 'B', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (B): Develop a documented procedure outlining prioritization criteria and resource allocation for processing accumulated transactions within regulatory timeframes after an incident.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper