  ('CISA-00964', 4, 'Hard', 'Incident Response Planning', 'What should the auditor FIRST recommend to address this gap?', 'Implement a new security awareness training program focused on identifying and avoiding phishing attacks.', 'Develop a detailed internal and external communication plan for incident response, outlining communication channels, designated spokespersons, and approval processes for releasing information, especially relating to national security risks.', 'Require all employees to immediately change their passwords and enable multi-factor authentication on all accounts.', 'Conduct a thorough forensic analysis of all affected workstations to determine the full extent of the compromise.', 'B', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (B): Develop a detailed internal and external communication plan for incident response, outlining communication channels, designated spokespersons, and approval processes for releasing information, especially relating to national security risks.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Manage