ructured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''re Wrong:  Option A: Increasing the storage capacity of the SIEM system to accommodate the growing volume of logs. → This approach either ignores the issue, escalates prematurely without documentation, or follows an unstructured process that creates audit gaps. Auditors must always follow structured procedures.  Option B: Implementing automated incident response playbooks to address common security alerts. → This option misses the audit objective or applies the wrong standard. Audit procedures must be aligned with scope and audit standards (ISACA, COBIT).  Option D: Hiring additional security analysts to monitor the SIEM dashboard around the clock. → This might be a procedural step but not the complete or correct response. Context matters in audit decisions.'),
  ('CISA-00984', 4, 'Hard', 'Monitoring and Logging', 'What is the PRIMARY concern for the auditor regarding this situation?', 'The lack of separation of duties between application administrators and security personnel.', 'The potential for unauthorized modification or deletion of audit logs by application administrators.', 'The inability to perform forensic analysis of the inventory management system in case of a security incident.', 'The risk of performance degradation on the inventory management system due to log storage.', 'B', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (B): The potential for unauthorized modification or deletion of audit logs by application administrators.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''re Wrong:  Option A: The lack of separation of duties between application administrators and security personnel. → This approach either