res management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''re Wrong:  Option A: Implement a centralized log management system with built-in time synchronization capabilities. → This approach either ignores the issue, escalates prematurely without documentation, or follows an unstructured process that creates audit gaps. Auditors must always follow structured procedures.  Option C: Deploy a Security Information and Event Management (SIEM) system to analyze the unsynchronized logs. → This option misses the audit objective or applies the wrong standard. Audit procedures must be aligned with scope and audit standards (ISACA, COBIT).  Option D: Increase the retention period of the audit logs to compensate for the lack of time synchronization. → This might be a procedural step but not the complete or correct response. Context matters in audit decisions.'),
  ('CISA-01004', 4, 'Medium', 'Monitoring and Logging', 'What is the MOST appropriate initial recommendation the auditor should make to enhance monitoring capabilities and address the ransomware threat?', 'Replace all medical devices with newer models that support robust logging capabilities.', 'Implement network-based intrusion detection and prevention systems (IDS/IPS) to monitor network traffic to and from the medical devices.', 'Isolate the medical devices on a separate network segment with limited access to the internet and other hospital networks.', 'Contract with a third-party security vendor to perform regular vulnerability assessments of the medical devices.', 'B', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (B): Implement network-based intrusion detection and prevention systems (IDS/IPS) to monitor network traffic to and from the medical devices.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future foll