er reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''re Wrong:  Option B: Immediately upgrade the server''s CPU to a faster processor. → This approach either ignores the issue, escalates prematurely without documentation, or follows an unstructured process that creates audit gaps. Auditors must always follow structured procedures.  Option C: Optimize database queries to reduce the CPU load during peak hours. → This option misses the audit objective or applies the wrong standard. Audit procedures must be aligned with scope and audit standards (ISACA, COBIT).  Option D: Implement a server virtualization solution to distribute the CPU load across multiple servers. → This might be a procedural step but not the complete or correct response. Context matters in audit decisions.'),
