hat you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''re Wrong:  Option B: The increased operational costs associated with managing the larger volume of log data. → This approach either ignores the issue, escalates prematurely without documentation, or follows an unstructured process that creates audit gaps. Auditors must always follow structured procedures.  Option C: The potential for false positives generated by the SIEM system due to the increased log volume. → This option misses the audit objective or applies the wrong standard. Audit procedures must be aligned with scope and audit standards (ISACA, COBIT).  Option D: The inadequacy of the newly implemented access control measures. → This might be a procedural step but not the complete or correct response. Context matters in audit decisions.'),
