  ('CISA-01033', 4, 'Medium', 'Capacity Planning and Performance', 'What should the auditor FIRST recommend regarding the disaster recovery plan?', 'Implementing a fully redundant e-commerce platform in a geographically diverse location.', 'Updating the disaster recovery plan to include specific scalability testing and capacity planning considerations for peak demand events.', 'Negotiating a higher service level agreement (SLA) with the cloud provider hosting the e-commerce platform.', 'Developing a detailed rollback plan to quickly revert to a previous stable version of the e-commerce platform in case of future outages.', 'B', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (B): Updating the disaster recovery plan to include specific scalability testing and capacity planning considerations for peak demand events.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''r