mentation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''re Wrong:  Option A: The potential for disruption of the automated batch processing job if MFA is enforced for the service account. → This approach either ignores the issue, escalates prematurely without documentation, or follows an unstructured process that creates audit gaps. Auditors must always follow structured procedures.  Option B: The increased administrative overhead associated with managing a service account that requires MFA. → This option misses the audit objective or applies the wrong standard. Audit procedures must be aligned with scope and audit standards (ISACA, COBIT).  Option C: The violation of the principle of least privilege, as the service account may have excessive permissions. → This might be a procedural step but not the complete or correct response. Context matters in audit decisions.'),
  ('CISA-01067', 4, 'Hard', 'Operations Security Controls', 'What should the auditor FIRST recommend to address this control gap?', 'Implement biometric access controls for all personnel entering the server room, replacing the existing keycard system.', 'Increase the frequency of physical access log reviews to monthly to improve detection of unauthorized access attempts.', 'Extend the scope of the quarterly physical access log review to include all personnel accessing the server room, regardless of their team or function.', 'Implement a video surveillance system with facial recognition capabilities to monitor all access to the server room.', 'C', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (C): Extend the scope of the quarterly physical access log review to include all personnel accessing the server room, regardless of their team or function.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  