heir payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''re Wrong:  Option A: Ensuring the supplier implements advanced threat detection systems to prevent future ransomware attacks. → This approach either ignores the issue, escalates prematurely without documentation, or follows an unstructured process that creates audit gaps. Auditors must always follow structured procedures.  Option C: Advising the company to diversify its supplier base to mitigate the impact of future disruptions. → This option misses the audit objective or applies the wrong standard. Audit procedures must be aligned with scope and audit standards (ISACA, COBIT).  Option D: Reviewing the company''s data backup and recovery procedures to ensure they can restore critical data in case of a similar incident. → This might be a procedural step but not the complete or correct response. Context matters in audit decisions.'),
  ('CISA-01090', 4, 'Hard', 'Third-Party Service Management', 'What is the auditor''s PRIMARY concern?', 'The potential for the 3PL provider to exceed the storage capacity allocated for the manufacturing firm''s data, leading to service degradation.', 'The risk of non-compliance with GDPR regulations due to inadequate data retention and destruction practices by the 3PL provider.', 'The lack of clear ownership and responsibility for data security between the manufacturing firm and the 3PL provider.', 'The difficulty in tracking and monitoring the 3PL provider''s compliance with the manufacturing firm''s internal security policies.', 'B', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (B): The risk of non-compliance with GDPR regulations due to inadequate data retention and destruction practices by the 3PL provider.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''