d lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''re Wrong:  Option A: The potential for the 3PL provider to exceed the storage capacity allocated for the manufacturing firm''s data, leading to service degradation. → This approach either ignores the issue, escalates prematurely without documentation, or follows an unstructured process that creates audit gaps. Auditors must always follow structured procedures.  Option C: The lack of clear ownership and responsibility for data security between the manufacturing firm and the 3PL provider. → This option misses the audit objective or applies the wrong standard. Audit procedures must be aligned with scope and audit standards (ISACA, COBIT).  Option D: The difficulty in tracking and monitoring the 3PL provider''s compliance with the manufacturing firm''s internal security policies. → This might be a procedural step but not the complete or correct response. Context matters in audit decisions.'),
