er authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''re Wrong:  Option A: Conduct yearly penetration tests of the regional hospital''s entire network. → This approach either ignores the issue, escalates prematurely without documentation, or follows an unstructured process that creates audit gaps. Auditors must always follow structured procedures.  Option B: Implement robust data encryption on all patient data transmitted over the VPN. → This option misses the audit objective or applies the wrong standard. Audit procedures must be aligned with scope and audit standards (ISACA, COBIT).  Option D: Purchase a separate, dedicated internet connection for radiology data transfer. → This might be a procedural step but not the complete or correct response. Context matters in audit decisions.'),
  ('CISA-01106', 4, 'Medium', 'Third-Party Service Management', 'What should the auditor recommend to MOST effectively reduce the risk of a security breach stemming from unpatched vulnerabilities?', 'Implement a vulnerability scanning solution on the hospital''s internal network.', 'Require the vendor to provide detailed reports on system patches applied and vulnerabilities addressed, including timelines and justifications for delays.', 'Negotiate a clause in the contract stating that the vendor is not liable for any security breaches resulting from unpatched vulnerabilities.', 'Limit the vendor''s access to only non-critical systems to reduce the potential impact of a breach.', 'B', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (B): Require the vendor to provide detailed reports on system patches applied and vulnerabilities addressed, including timelines and justifications for delays.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purp