t and in transit for all data processed by the system. → This approach either ignores the issue, escalates prematurely without documentation, or follows an unstructured process that creates audit gaps. Auditors must always follow structured procedures.  Option C: Performing penetration testing on the new claims processing system to identify vulnerabilities. → This option misses the audit objective or applies the wrong standard. Audit procedures must be aligned with scope and audit standards (ISACA, COBIT).  Option D: Implementing a data loss prevention (DLP) solution to monitor and prevent the exfiltration of sensitive data. → This might be a procedural step but not the complete or correct response. Context matters in audit decisions.', 'Developing a data classification policy and procedures is the foundational step. It provides a framework for identifying, categorizing, and handling data based on its sensitivity and regulatory requirements. Without proper classification, other security measures will be less effective and may not adequately protect the data.', 'See reasoning above for explanation of correct vs incorrect choices', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (B): Developing and implementing a data classification policy and associated procedures, including training for employees.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''re Wrong:  Option A: Implementing data encryption at rest and in transit for all data processed by the system. → This approach either ignores the issue, escalates prematurely without documentation, or follows an unstructured process that creates audit gaps. Auditors must always follow structured procedures.  Option C: Performing penetration testing on the new claims processing system to identify vulnerabilities. → This option misses the audit objective or applies the wrong standard. Audit procedures must be aligned with scope and audit standards (ISACA, COBIT).  Option D: Implementing a data loss prevention (DLP) solution to monitor and prevent the exfiltration of sensitive data. → This might be a procedural step but not the complete or correct response. Context matters in audit decisions.'),
  ('CISA-01124', 5, 'Medium', 'Data Classification and Handling', 'What is the PRIMARY concern for the auditor regarding this inconsistency in data classification?', 'Potential violation of service level agreements (SLAs) with the cloud provider.', 'Increased cost of managing the cloud-based CRM system.', 'Inadequate protection of sensitive customer data due to misaligned security controls.', 'Difficulties in performing data analytics and reporting due to inconsistent data formats.', 'C', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (C): Inadequate protection of sensitive customer data due to misaligned security controls.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''re Wrong:  Option A: Potential violation of service level agreements (SLAs) with the cloud provider. → This approach either ignores the issue, escalates prematurely without documentation, or fol