  ('CISA-01142', 5, 'Hard', 'Encryption and Key Management', 'What is the MOST important action for the auditor to recommend?', 'Immediately isolate the SCADA system from the corporate network to prevent lateral movement of attackers.', 'Require the system administrator to immediately change all default HSM passwords and strengthen access controls.', 'Implement multi-factor authentication for all users accessing the SCADA system to enhance security.', 'Conduct a penetration test of the SCADA system to identify potential vulnerabilities beyond the HSM configuration.', 'B', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (B): Require the system administrator to immediately change all default HSM passwords and strengthen access controls.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''re Wrong:  Option A: Immediately isolate the SCADA system from the corporate network to prevent lateral movement of attackers. → This approach either ignores the issue, escalates prematurely without documentation, or follows an unstructured process that creates audit gaps. Auditors must always follow structured procedures.  Option C: Implement multi-factor authentication for all users accessing the SCADA system to enhance security. → This option misses the audit objective or applies the wrong standard. Audit procedures must be aligned with scope and audit standards (ISACA, COBIT).  Option D: Conduct a penetration test of the SCADA system to identify potential vulnerabilities beyond the HSM configuration. → This might be a procedural step but not the complete or correct response. Context matters in audit decisions.', 'The MOST important action is to immediately change the default HSM passwords and strengthen access controls. Using default passwords creates a significant and easily exploitable vulnerability that could allow unauthorized access to the keys protecting the SCADA system, resulting in a compromise of the manufacturing process.', 'See reasoning above for explanation of correct vs incorrect choices', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (B): Require the system administrator to immediately change all default HSM passwords and strengthen access controls.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementa