  ('CISA-01172', 5, 'Hard', 'Access Control and Identity Management', 'What is the MOST significant risk associated with this approach?', 'Inconsistent patch management practices leading to increased attack surface in the OT/ICS environment.', 'Increased operational costs associated with maintaining two separate patching systems.', 'Potential for conflicts between patches applied to IT and OT/ICS environments.', 'Reduced efficiency in the IT environment due to the complexity of the automated patching system.', 'A', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (A): Inconsistent patch management practices leading to increased attack surface in the OT/ICS environment.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer represents the best practice approach for the scenario presented. It aligns with ISACA standards, COBIT framework principles, and proven audit methodologies. The reasoning is grounded in risk management fundamentals and control design best practices.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: In a typical enterprise scenario, the organization that follows this answer''s approach achieves better outcomes. For instance, proper implementation results in: • Reduced operational risk • Better compliance with regulations • Improved stakeholder confidence • More efficient resource allocation • Better decision-making with proper information  The alternative approaches lead to gaps, inefficiencies, or increased risk.  WHY THIS MATTERS: Adopting this best practice ensures: • Alignment with industry standards • Reduced risk of audit findings • Better business-technology outcomes • More effective control frameworks • Improved organizational maturity  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''re Wrong:  Option B: Increased operational costs associated with maintaining two separate patching systems. → This approach has a critical flaw: [specific reason why wrong answer is problematic relative to context]  Option C: Potential for conflicts between patches applied to IT and OT/ICS environments. → This is incomplete or applies the wrong stan