verity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''re Wrong:  Option A: Implementing multi-factor authentication (MFA) for all SIS users to reduce the risk of unauthorized access. → This approach either ignores the issue, escalates prematurely without documentation, or follows an unstructured process that creates audit gaps. Auditors must always follow structured procedures.  Option C: Conducting regular vulnerability assessments and penetration testing on the SIS infrastructure. → This option misses the audit objective or applies the wrong standard. Audit procedures must be aligned with scope and audit standards (ISACA, COBIT).  Option D: Establishing a comprehensive incident response plan specifically tailored to data breaches involving the SIS. → This might be a procedural step but not the complete or correct response. Context matters in audit decisions.'),
  ('CISA-01184', 5, 'Hard', 'Data Loss Prevention', 'What is the MOST important control deficiency the auditor should highlight?', 'Insufficient integration of the DLP solution with the organization''s intrusion detection system (IDS).', 'The limited scope of the DLP ruleset, failing to protect all types of sensitive data assets.', 'Lack of user awareness training regarding the organization''s data loss prevention policies.', 'The absence of a formal process for regularly reviewing and updating the DLP ruleset.', 'B', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (B): The limited scope of the DLP ruleset, failing to protect all types of sensitive data assets.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''re Wrong:  Option A: Insufficient integration of the DLP solution with the organization''s intrusion detection system (IDS). → This approach either ignores t