a encryption across all storage locations within the cloud data lake. → This approach either ignores the issue, escalates prematurely without documentation, or follows an unstructured process that creates audit gaps. Auditors must always follow structured procedures.  Option B: Extending data masking techniques to cover sensitive manufacturing process data and intellectual property, even in non-production environments. → This option misses the audit objective or applies the wrong standard. Audit procedures must be aligned with scope and audit standards (ISACA, COBIT).  Option D: Implementing multi-factor authentication for all users accessing the cloud data lake. → This might be a procedural step but not the complete or correct response. Context matters in audit decisions.', 'A comprehensive data classification policy is the foundation for effective data loss prevention. Without proper classification, the organization will struggle to consistently identify and protect all sensitive data. Without that classification, the effectiveness of all other controls are impacted.', 'See reasoning above for explanation of correct vs incorrect choices', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (C): Establishing a comprehensive data classification policy to identify and categorize all sensitive data stored in the data lake.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud)